ce:section.ce:para:
MCR-ALS algorithm is performed on real sample data with following restriction, non-negativity on concentration as well as spectral data and unimodality on concentration data. Principal component analysis estimates two principal components with 97.3% of variations and <3% of residuals. The residuals are mostly scattering or non-emissive responses from the raw water sample. Evolving factor analysis predicts the variable window (wavelength range) in which white emitting mixture shows the variation in presence of HMI. The soft MCR-ALS resolves two unique emissions with variation of HMI and residuals and are shown in Fig. 6
                        . The concentration correlation was made by inputting the initial estimation of the lowest concentration as 10 μM and yields the quantitative visualisation of the rest of the four real samples. Percentage (%) recovery of the four samples with reliability factors are also calculated (Table 2). In order to extract exact information of unknown samples, a calibration set of known composition can be created followed by applying correlation constraint yields precise composition. The precision and accuracy of the methodology is tabulated as RMSEP values (Table 3
                        ). The resolved spectral data shows only polyphenolic emission, not red emission of anthocyanin (Fig. 6b). This again confirms the mechanism of complex formation of cadmium ions with the polyphenolic part of anthocyanin. The concentration of HMIs is also calculated from the resolved data with very good percentage recovery (RMSEP <0.3) [51].
